<font color="#FF0000">PTSD COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Mar 21 23:34:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chris, Doc Spatz, Alex, and everyone else, <br><br>
I have been surfing the net for PTSD information since last August when I received the written report of my diagnosis. I posted some of the better stuff on a web page I started a short while ago. You are all invited to stop by. Contributions and comments are appreciated. The page really belongs to everybody.<br><br>
http://www.netcom.com/~art16/NamVet.html<br><br>
Alex, I too am going through the system. We should compare notes off line by e-mail sometime.<br><br>
One of the most difficult parts of my trials with PTSD was the chilling realization that my 27 year flirtation with the other side really had a name. I am it and it is me, a forever kind of yin-yang kinship that strangely brings me closer to what I am and what I was, what I became, what I lost, and what I am now rediscovering inside in places long forgotten and buried out of fear, pain, and self but protecively imposed exile. The terror of that first flirtation of reaching out to the world and to life remains with me still, an everpresent reminder that I, too, am human, and that this peculiar affliction is a very, very, very, human thing. I am beginning to be no longer ashamed that I am human. In spite of the everpresent pain of it all, this and my experiences are no longer secrets, and the people who respect this honesty I number among my true friends. <br><br>
I once remarked that I had a feeling I thought in some way brought me closer to other survivors of traumatic events. Rape victims, adult children of alcoholics, abused children, and the survivors of countless other horrors now have a place of respect in my mind and thoughts. There go we all.<br><br>
Chris, we all understand. The honor of FNG bestowed on you by Chet says it all and from all of us. We mean it.<br><br>
&quot;Arty&quot;
